tweet_text:
We often focus on the wrong problem when asking for help. Instead of asking about X, we end up asking about Y. Let me explain...

Say you're implementing image¬†upload in your service, and while doing so, you get stuck converting a base64 string into an image. So, you ask for help decoding base64.

But the real problem isn't decoding base64, it's actually handling image uploads. If you had asked about photo uploads, someone might have shown you an easier way to solve it all.

That's the classic XY problem: you ask about your assumed solution Y, instead of explaining the actual problem X you want to solve.

- say what you are really trying to do
- don't assume your solution is the only way
- explain the full problem, not just the code snippet
- describe what you have already tried

Before you ask, check yourself: are you asking about Y or explaining X? Don't get trapped by the XY problem, solve the right issue and not just your guess at it.

Asking the right question can only take you to the right answer.

tweet_text:
We often focus on the wrong problem when asking for help. Instead of asking about X, we end up asking about Y. Let me explain...

Say you're implementing image¬†upload in your service, and while doing so, you get stuck converting a base64 string into an image. So, you ask for help decoding base64.

But the real problem isn't decoding base64, it's actually handling image uploads. If you had asked about photo uploads, someone might have shown you an easier way to solve it all.

That's the classic XY problem: you ask about your assumed solution Y, instead of explaining the actual problem X you want to solve.

- say what you are really trying to do
- don't assume your solution is the only way
- explain the full problem, not just the code snippet
- describe what you have already tried

Before you ask, check yourself: are you asking about Y or explaining X? Don't get trapped by the XY problem, solve the right issue and not just your guess at it.

Asking the right question can only take you to the right answer.

tweet_text:
you use tool A - it's great and does what you need pretty well

then you hear tool A is getting an update that breaks things. this is upsetting - now you feel compelled to do work to update something that was working for what seems like marginal benefits

you wish author of tool A would just let it be and not chase every shiny idea

now let's look at it from the author's pov

you build tool A - wow a lot of people like it and find it useful, that feels great

one day someone floats an idea for how tool A could be better. hm it's interesting but it would be disruptive and you don't want to upset your users

the weeks go on you can't stop thinking about it but you ultimately hope it was probably not too great an idea anyway

then one day someone implements the idea and builds tool B - they have no users to upset or anything to lose so why not just try

turns out the idea was quite good and while not many tool A users are switching, most new projects are opting for tool B. why pick the worse option when starting from scratch?

so now you scramble to implement this idea in tool A - you move slow because you have to figure out a migration path and it's not as smooth as people want anyway

and ultimately it's too late - tool A just feels like a worse version of tool B

eventually the tool A user base decays and as people switch jobs they're upset that everyone is only hiring for tool B

what was wrong with tool A they ask, why is everyone chasing the newest thing!

---

when you are frustrated at changes this is the dynamic that's going on behind the scenes

yes sometimes the "new idea" ends up not being a good one and bad judgement calls can be made

but can you really blame any party here? it's just the reality of the world being a dynamic, evolving, competitive place where making decisions can be pretty challenging

if you feel like you can do a better job - you should

and guess what, this exact dynamic that you complain about is exactly what prevents tool A from ruling forever and allows you to go build tool B and do that better job

tweet_text:
We often focus on the wrong problem when asking for help. Instead of asking about X, we end up asking about Y. Let me explain...

Say you're implementing image¬†upload in your service, and while doing so, you get stuck converting a base64 string into an image. So, you ask for help decoding base64.

But the real problem isn't decoding base64, it's actually handling image uploads. If you had asked about photo uploads, someone might have shown you an easier way to solve it all.

That's the classic XY problem: you ask about your assumed solution Y, instead of explaining the actual problem X you want to solve.

- say what you are really trying to do
- don't assume your solution is the only way
- explain the full problem, not just the code snippet
- describe what you have already tried

Before you ask, check yourself: are you asking about Y or explaining X? Don't get trapped by the XY problem, solve the right issue and not just your guess at it.

Asking the right question can only take you to the right answer.

tweet_text:
you use tool A - it's great and does what you need pretty well

then you hear tool A is getting an update that breaks things. this is upsetting - now you feel compelled to do work to update something that was working for what seems like marginal benefits

you wish author of tool A would just let it be and not chase every shiny idea

now let's look at it from the author's pov

you build tool A - wow a lot of people like it and find it useful, that feels great

one day someone floats an idea for how tool A could be better. hm it's interesting but it would be disruptive and you don't want to upset your users

the weeks go on you can't stop thinking about it but you ultimately hope it was probably not too great an idea anyway

then one day someone implements the idea and builds tool B - they have no users to upset or anything to lose so why not just try

turns out the idea was quite good and while not many tool A users are switching, most new projects are opting for tool B. why pick the worse option when starting from scratch?

so now you scramble to implement this idea in tool A - you move slow because you have to figure out a migration path and it's not as smooth as people want anyway

and ultimately it's too late - tool A just feels like a worse version of tool B

eventually the tool A user base decays and as people switch jobs they're upset that everyone is only hiring for tool B

what was wrong with tool A they ask, why is everyone chasing the newest thing!

---

when you are frustrated at changes this is the dynamic that's going on behind the scenes

yes sometimes the "new idea" ends up not being a good one and bad judgement calls can be made

but can you really blame any party here? it's just the reality of the world being a dynamic, evolving, competitive place where making decisions can be pretty challenging

if you feel like you can do a better job - you should

and guess what, this exact dynamic that you complain about is exactly what prevents tool A from ruling forever and allows you to go build tool B and do that better job

We often focus on the wrong problem when asking for help. Instead of asking about X, we end up asking about Y. Let me explain...

Say you're implementing image¬†upload in your service, and while doing so, you get stuck converting a base64 string into an image. So, you ask for help decoding base64.

But the real problem isn't decoding base64, it's actually handling image uploads. If you had asked about photo uploads, someone might have shown you an easier way to solve it all.

That's the classic XY problem: you ask about your assumed solution Y, instead of explaining the actual problem X you want to solve.

- say what you are really trying to do
- don't assume your solution is the only way
- explain the full problem, not just the code snippet
- describe what you have already tried

Before you ask, check yourself: are you asking about Y or explaining X? Don't get trapped by the XY problem, solve the right issue and not just your guess at it.

Asking the right question can only take you to the right answer.

tweet_text:
you use tool A - it's great and does what you need pretty well

then you hear tool A is getting an update that breaks things. this is upsetting - now you feel compelled to do work to update something that was working for what seems like marginal benefits

you wish author of tool A would just let it be and not chase every shiny idea

now let's look at it from the author's pov

you build tool A - wow a lot of people like it and find it useful, that feels great

one day someone floats an idea for how tool A could be better. hm it's interesting but it would be disruptive and you don't want to upset your users

the weeks go on you can't stop thinking about it but you ultimately hope it was probably not too great an idea anyway

then one day someone implements the idea and builds tool B - they have no users to upset or anything to lose so why not just try

turns out the idea was quite good and while not many tool A users are switching, most new projects are opting for tool B. why pick the worse option when starting from scratch?

so now you scramble to implement this idea in tool A - you move slow because you have to figure out a migration path and it's not as smooth as people want anyway

and ultimately it's too late - tool A just feels like a worse version of tool B

eventually the tool A user base decays and as people switch jobs they're upset that everyone is only hiring for tool B

what was wrong with tool A they ask, why is everyone chasing the newest thing!

---

when you are frustrated at changes this is the dynamic that's going on behind the scenes

yes sometimes the "new idea" ends up not being a good one and bad judgement calls can be made

but can you really blame any party here? it's just the reality of the world being a dynamic, evolving, competitive place where making decisions can be pretty challenging

if you feel like you can do a better job - you should

and guess what, this exact dynamic that you complain about is exactly what prevents tool A from ruling forever and allows you to go build tool B and do that better job
